.docname {D. Selection and Searching}
.include {docs}

These glyphs are how you cut, join, filter, search, and index data.

Selection glyphs are where array programming starts to feel practical. You can sort, take the first few rows, filter with a mask, find positions, and reconstruct arrays without writing explicit loops.

Keep the distinction between `‚äè select` and `‚ä° pick` clear. `‚äè` selects rows and can return many rows. `‚ä°` indexes into an array and is the tool you reach for when an index describes a position inside the structure.

## Joining, Indexing, Reshaping Rows

| Glyph | Name | Meaning | Example |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `‚äü` | couple | make two rows | `‚äü [1 2] [3 4]` |
| `‚äÇ` | join | append arrays | `‚äÇ [1 2] [3 4]` |
| `‚äè` | select | select rows by indices | `‚äè 2_0 [8 3 9]` |
| `‚ä°` | pick | pick one row or element | `‚ä° 1 [8 3 9]` |
| `‚Üô` | take | take rows | `‚Üô 3 [8 3 9 2 0]` |
| `‚Üò` | drop | drop rows | `‚Üò 3 [8 3 9 2 0]` |
| `‚Üª` | rotate | rotate rows | `‚Üª 2 [8 3 9 2 0]` |
| `‚§∏` | orient | reorder axes | `‚§∏ 1 ¬∞‚ñ≥2_3_4` |
| `‚ñΩ` | keep | filter or repeat rows | `‚ñΩ 1_0_1 "abc"` |

`‚ñΩ keep` is the workhorse for filtering. It takes counts or a mask, then keeps that many copies of each row. With a boolean mask, `1` means keep and `0` means discard. This is why comparison glyphs are so useful: they produce masks that can feed directly into `‚ñΩ`.

`‚Üô take`, `‚Üò drop`, and `‚Üª rotate` are about position rather than content. Use them after sorting or when the row order already has meaning, such as time-series data.

## Searching and Set-Like Work

| Glyph | Name | Meaning | Example |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `‚äö` | where | indices of nonzero values | `‚äö [0 1 0 1]` |
| `‚ó¥` | deduplicate | remove duplicate rows | `‚ó¥ "banana"` |
| `‚äõ` | classify | classify unique rows | `‚äõ "banana"` |
| `‚ßÜ` | occurrences | count prior occurrences | `‚ßÜ "banana"` |
| `‚ó∞` | unique | first occurrence mask, deprecated | `‚ó∞ "banana"` |
| `‚âç` | match | exact shape/type match | `‚âç 1_2_3 [1 2 3]` |
| `‚åï` | find | mark start of occurrences | `‚åï "ab" "abracadabra"` |
| `‚¶∑` | mask | mark full occurrences | `‚¶∑ "ab" "abracadabra"` |
| `‚àä` | memberof | membership test | `‚àä [1 2 3] [2 4]` |
| `‚®Ç` | indexin | first index in searched array | `‚®Ç [1 2 3] 2` |
| `‚äó` | indexof | old index direction, deprecated | `‚äó 2 [1 2 3]` |
| `‚ä•` | base | base digits | `‚ä• 10 123` |
| `‚ãØ` | bits | binary digits | `‚ãØ 27` |

The search glyphs split into two families. `‚åï`, `‚¶∑`, `‚àä`, and `‚®Ç` ask questions about membership or location. `‚ó¥`, `‚äõ`, and `‚ßÜ` summarize repeated rows. For text, these work on characters; for matrices, they work on rows.

